President Barack Obama has proclaimed October 2016 as National Youth Substance Use and Substance Use Disorder Prevention Month. The proclamation emphasizes the importance of preventing substance use among young people and the devastating impact it can have on their lives. The President highlights the need for collective effort in communities to ensure more Americans live healthy and productive lives. The National Drug Control Strategy is mentioned as a means to amplify prevention efforts and support communities with evidence-based strategies. The President also emphasizes the dangers of prescription drug misuse and the current opioid epidemic, calling on Congress to provide funding for treatment services. The proclamation encourages the involvement of parents, guardians, teachers, coaches, and the healthcare community in promoting substance use prevention efforts. The President calls upon all Americans to engage in programs and activities to reduce youth substance use and substance use disorders within their communities.